<PageLayout
  title="Melanotan and Melanotan II: what they are, why they tan you, and the real risks"
  kicker="Explainer"
  description="The 'tanning peptides' sold online are synthetic versions of a melanocortin hormone. Here's the actual pharmacology, how the two melanotans relate to the approved drugs they spawned, and the documented risks — explained plainly, not sold."
  updated="2026"
>
  <p>
    Search for a way to tan without the sun and you will quickly meet
    "melanotan" — peptides sold online as injections or nasal sprays that
    genuinely darken skin. They are real pharmacology, not a gimmick: synthetic
    relatives of the body's own pigment hormone, α-MSH. But the most popular one
    is also unapproved everywhere, sold illegally, and tied to documented harms.
    This page explains what these compounds are and why they do what they do — it
    is education, not endorsement, and not medical advice.
  </p>

  <h2>Two melanotans — and the medicines they became</h2>
  <p>
    The confusing part is that "melanotan" names a small family, and most of it
    grew up to be legitimate. All of it traces to work at the University of
    Arizona to make stable analogues of α-MSH.<Cite n={1} />
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Melanotan-I</strong> — the more selective
      <a href="/receptors/mc1r">MC1R</a> analogue. It became an
      <em>approved drug</em>: afamelanotide (Scenesse), a controlled-release
      implant for a rare light-sensitivity disorder. See the
      <a href="/therapeutics#afamelanotide">therapeutics entry</a>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Melanotan II (MT-II)</strong> — a more potent, <em>non-selective</em>
      melanocortin agonist that hits MC1R, MC3R, MC4R and MC5R. It was the one
      pushed as a tanning agent, and it is the one that <em>never</em> became a
      medicine. This is the "melanotan" sold on the grey market.<Cite n={1} />
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Its offspring</strong> — bremelanotide (Vyleesi), derived from the
      MT-II scaffold, became an approved treatment for low sexual desire. See the
      full <a href="/bremelanotide">bremelanotide / PT-141 explainer</a>.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    So two of the three melanotan-lineage molecules cleared trials and reached
    pharmacies under controlled doses and forms. The middle one — MT-II — stayed
    in vials marked "research chemical, not for human use," which is how it dodges
    the rules it can't pass.<Cite n={2} />
  </p>

  <h2>Why it tans you</h2>
  <p>
    The tanning is straightforward melanocortin biology. MT-II activates
    <a href="/receptors/mc1r">MC1R</a> on your melanocytes, which raises cyclic
    AMP and pushes pigment production toward brown-black eumelanin — the same
    switch the sun's UV would normally flip, but triggered chemically and
    <em>without</em> sunlight.<Cite n={1} /> That is genuinely why it appeals to people
    who burn rather than tan: it can build pigment in skin that otherwise won't.
  </p>

  <h2>Why it also does much more than tan</h2>
  <p>
    Here is the catch the marketing skips: MT-II is <em>non-selective</em>, so it
    doesn't only hit the pigment receptor. Activating
    <a href="/receptors/mc4r">MC4R</a> in the brain is why users report nausea
    (commonly 50% or more), facial flushing, loss of appetite, drowsiness,
    yawning, and spontaneous erections — the last effect so reliable that it
    became the entire basis of the spin-off drug bremelanotide.<Cite n={1} /> If
    you want the full mechanism of why melanocortin agonists make you queasy and
    darken, see <a href="/effects">why melanocortin agonists make you queasy and
    tan</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>The risks that matter</h2>
  <p>
    Beyond the everyday side effects, three categories of risk are why
    dermatologists and regulators single this compound out.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Moles and melanoma.</strong> MT-II darkens existing moles and is
      associated with the rapid appearance of new ones. Dermatologists' deeper
      concern is that driving pigment cells this hard could accelerate already-
      abnormal moles toward melanoma, and there are case reports of melanoma
      emerging during or shortly after use.<Cite n={1} /><Cite n={4} /> Causation
      isn't proven, but the mechanism is plausible and the reports are real — and
      a chemical tan can mask exactly the mole changes you're meant to watch for.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Serious, if uncommon, events.</strong> Published case reports include
      rhabdomyolysis (muscle breakdown), kidney dysfunction, and neurological
      effects after MT-II injection.<Cite n={1} /> These come from uncontrolled use,
      where dose and product quality are unknown variables.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>An unregulated product.</strong> Because it is sold illegally, no
      one verifies what is in the vial — purity, dose, sterility, or
      contaminants — and self-injection or nasal use adds its own risks.<Cite n={2} /><Cite n={3} />
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>It is not approved, and not legal to sell</h2>
  <p>
    Melanotan II has never completed the safety trials a medicine requires, and it
    is unlicensed in the US, UK, EU, and Australia. The FDA, the UK's MHRA,
    Australia's TGA, and European regulators have all warned against it, and
    regulators have moved against sellers.<Cite n={2} /><Cite n={3} /><Cite n={4} />
    The "research chemical" label on what's clearly being marketed for human use is
    a way around approval, not evidence of safety.
  </p>

  <h2>The honest bottom line</h2>
  <p>
    The biology is real: melanotan does build a sunless tan, through exactly the
    MC1R pathway this site describes. But the popular version, MT-II, is
    unapproved, illegal to sell, of unknown quality, and carries genuine
    documented risks — including to the very moles a tan can hide. The only
    approved melanocortin that builds protective pigment, afamelanotide, exists
    for a rare medical condition, not cosmetic tanning. There is, at present, no
    approved melanocortin tanning product. We document the science so the decision
    is an informed one.
  </p>

  <div class="not-prose mt-8 rounded-lg border border-[var(--border)] bg-[var(--accent-soft)] p-6 text-sm leading-relaxed">
